Written to `tools/title-loop/docs/19-55b161b/feedback.md`.

**Summary of the analysis:**

The single failure (`Smażona zielona fasolka`) is a **regression introduced in iteration 19** by the `commonShort2` expansion.

**Root cause:** Adding Polish prepositions (`na`, `po`, `od`, `za`, `co`) to `commonShort2` was the right fix for titles like "Krem Grzybowy ze Śmietaną", but it had a collateral effect: Polish body-text lines containing those prepositions now pass `passesHardFilters`. In this file, `"Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno"` ("Serve hot or cold", line 23) and `"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek..."` (line 21) were previously garble-filtered because `"na"` wasn't in the whitelist — now they enter the candidate pool.

**Failure path:** The bilingual detection correctly suppresses `GREEN BEANS BORKEUM` (the ALL_CAPS translation), leaving zero ALL_CAPS candidates in `selected`. The multi-title guard's "zero ALL_CAPS → keep all" branch then fires, producing a multi-title result like `"Smażona zielona fasolka + Podawaj no gorqco lub na zimno"` instead of the expected single title.

**Why this is real-file only:** Generated files use English OCR content where cooking instructions are caught by `looksLikeCookingInstruction`. Polish cooking verbs (`Podawaj`, `Dodaj`, etc.) aren't in that list.
