{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011UMQhcnPQ5yPboczZtEPzY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is very helpful. In iteration 18, \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" was a **yes** — it passed! But in iteration 19, it's a **no**. Something in the iteration 19 code changes broke it.\n\nThe iteration 19 code was committed as \"55b161b title-extraction: iteration 18\" (wait, that's confusing naming). Let me check - the results file for iteration 19 (`19-55b161b`) shows \"Smażona zielona fasolka - no\", while iteration 18 (`18-1d256ae`) showed it as \"yes\".\n\n\nNow I need to look at the actual diff between those two commits to understand what changed. Looking at the current code, I can see there's logic around line 663-664 that's suppressing translation candidates before computing the threshold so their bonuses don't inflate things beyond the mixed-case title's reach. The implementation is checking position ≤ 2 for local proximity rather than global ALL_CAPS count, which means section headers later in the document are ignored.\n\nBut wait—the comment explicitly mentions \"Smażona zielona fasolka GREEN BEANS BORKEUM 그린빈 볶음\" as an example, and that's the exact file that's failing now. The bilingual detection code was added in iteration 19 specifically to handle this case, yet it's still not working. Let me trace through the logic more carefully to see where the breakdown is happening. Checking the caps coalescing logic for \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" — it has three words, so it doesn't qualify for coalescing since the threshold is two words or fewer. The Korean line doesn't start with a continuation character, so it stays separate. Now I'm evaluating whether \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" passes the hard filters, starting with its length. I'm tracing through how the code strips non-ASCII characters from the Polish text—the ż gets removed, leaving just ASCII letters, so \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" becomes