 to sautéed green beans), the similarity score likely exceeds the 0.4 threshold, making \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" a translation candidate. Even if that method fails, the word overlap check would trigger layout detection and still flag it as a translation. So I'm adding \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" to the translation candidates list and now filtering the scored results by threshold.\n\nNow I'm checking which text entries actually contain their translation candidates—\"Smażona zielona fasolka\" doesn't include the translation, so it stays, while \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" matches itself and gets removed, and the combined entry gets removed because it includes the translation substring. Since \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" was the only structural heading and it's now identified as a translation, I'm clearing it from the structural headings and removing its bonus from the scoring. The threshold filtering continues with this updated scoring. I'm checking whether other candidates in the document might actually score higher than the title. Let me trace through what \"Przygotowanie\" would look like after normalization and scoring to see if it could be a stronger match. isLikelyGarbled(\"Przvgetowanie\") passes the filters because it has enough vowels and doesn't match the garbling patterns, but it's actually a typo of \"Przygotowanie\" which is a section label—the embedding score would catch it as low confidence for a recipe title. Let me trace through the code logic more carefully, particularly around the bilingual detection and how it checks for section headers early in the document. Looking at the git history, the bilingual detection logic was added in iteration 19, but the test case regressed—it was passing in iteration 18 and failing after. The code that's supposed to suppress translation candidates before computing the threshold is already there, so something else must have changed that broke it.\n\nLet me trace through what happens after the bilingual fix is applied: if \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" gets correctly identified as a translation and filtered out, then the first structural heading becomes undefined, and the scoring should recalculate based on the remaining candidates. The issue might be in how the threshold is being computed or applied to the final selection. I'm checking whether the score calculation actually passes the threshold—if rawScore is positive, then 1.12 times it definitely beats 0.7 times it, so it passes. But if rawScore turns out negative, the score would fail since it'd be below whatever positive threshold gets set. Let me think about whether \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" could actually have a negative rawScore by comparing it against the title reference.\n\nSince \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" means \"sautéed green beans\" and should semantically match recipe titles much better than ingredient lists or noise, the title similarity should dominate and give a positive rawScore. But I'm wondering if there's a filtering step that's accidentally removing this entry before it even gets scored.\n\nChecking the filtering logic...\n\nFiltering out entries...\n\nI need to trace through the logic more carefully—the position values stored in the candidates array correspond to line indices in the merged/coalesced data, not the original file positions. Let me reconsider which entries should actually remain after this filtering step. \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" qualifies as prePos0 since it's at position 0 and not all caps, while \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\" gets filtered into nearbyAllCaps because it's at position 1, all caps, and marked as \"single\" origin. I need to verify whether the caps coalescing step would have changed \"GREEN BEANS BORKEUM\"'s origin status, or if it remains \"single\" since it's a standalone line with multiple words. I'm hitting a dead end trying to trace through this analytically, so let me compare what actually changed between iteration 18 and 19 to find the real issue.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_seque