rds\n    - unicodeLetters check\n\n: text.match(/\\p{L}/gu) would include Korean characters, so unicodeLetters.length > letters.length (more Unicode letters than ASCII letters)\n    - words.length = 8 > 1, so skip the single-word check\n    - No internal lowercase→uppercase transition (that's only for single words)\n    - Starts with uppercase S: OK\n    - No \". \" boundary\n    - Multi-word garbled check: looking at words starting with lowercase:\n      - \"zielona\": lowercase z, after removing non-ASCII it's 7 chars > 2 → not flagged\n      - \"fasolka\": lowercase f, 7 chars > 2 → not flagged\n      - \"그린빈\" and \"볶음\": these don't match /^[a-z]/ since they start with Korean characters\n    - No garbled word found, so isLikelyGarbled = false\n    - looksLikeCookingInstruction: checking if it starts with a cooking verb...\n\nNow checking if this looks like a cooking instruction by examining the first word.\n\nThe text passes all the validation checks, so it's a valid candidate for the bilingual detection step. When I run the bilingual filter, I'm checking if the English portion appears as a substring within the full text, accounting for word boundaries and case-insensitive matching.\n\nNow I need to look more carefully at what actually changed between these iterations. Let me examine the full diff to see where the bilingual detection logic was modified.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1293,"cache_read_input_tokens":70833,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1293},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fe1e814e-1a51-4be7-ba64-e09ed2a4511e","uuid":"204fbe77-bba7-474a-93b1-5073a09b2fea"}
