{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Qkwf49Uw1trTc81wV7WfbX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the issue! The `pos0Compounds` logic in iteration 19 is:\n\n```javascript\nconst pos0Compounds = selected.filter((s) => s.position === 0);\nif (pos0Compounds.length > 0) {\n  selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n    if (s.position === 0) return true;\n    const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n    return !pos0Compounds.some(\n      (p0) =>\n        p0.position + 10 < s.position &&\n        s.text.length < p0.text.length &&\n        p0.text.toLowerCase().includes(sLower)\n    );\n  });\n}\n```\n\nThis filters out candidates that appear more than 10 lines after a position-0 compound and are shorter substrings of it. Since \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" is at position 0, it gets kept, and the logic wouldn't explain the failure. Let me examine the `joinsToProtect` logic instead.\n\nI'm looking at how multi-word joins are protected by removing their component single-word candidates when enough of those singles are present.\n\nNow I'm wondering about the specific case in the Smażona file—could a 2-line join survive where \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" acts as one of its components? But that doesn't quite work since \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" is already three words, not a single word that would match against a join's word list. The `some()` check only matches if a join contains that exact multi-word phrase as a single space-separated element, which is impossible, so \"Smażona zielona fasolka\" would never be flagged for removal. I'm wondering if the real issue is that `scoredForThreshold` contains inflated values that push the threshold too high, preventing this single from passing the score check in the first place.\n\nLet me trace back through the data flow: `scored` comes from `rawScored`, which comes from `candidates`, which comes from `buildCandidates`. I need to check if iteration 19's changes to `buildCandidates` are generating additional candidates that weren't present in iteration 18. The main change allows 2-line and 3-line joins from section-label lines when the join has at least 3 words and the first line isn't in `ALWAYS_BLOCK_JOIN_LABELS`. In the Smażona file, \"SKLADNIKI\" is a section label but it's already blocked because it's in that list, so no new candidates come from there. I'm checking what other lines might be generating new candidates now. Looking at line 19 \"nasiono sezamu\", it's only 14 characters so it passes the length check. Checking the garbling detection: the letters form a 13-character string with a vowel ratio of about 46%, which seems reasonable, and it's a single word with enough unicode letters to not be flagged as garbled. It's not a section label either, and it starts with lowercase, so this line should pass through the filters.\n\nFor line 21, the text starts with uppercase 'N' and contains several short words, but when I check the individual components—\"ogr\" has 3 characters which exceeds the threshold for being flagged as a short word, so this line doesn't trigger the filtering conditions either. The text is about 65 characters, so it passes the length check. \"No potelni rozprowadż oliwę z oliwek i smaż crosnek na duzym ogr\" would've been a candidate in iteration 18 too since the hard filters are the same—it doesn't start with an English cooking verb, so the new cooking instruction check doesn't filter it out either. I need to dig deeper into what actually changed between iterations, maybe the bilingual detection logic is where the difference lies.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":684,"cache_read_input_tokens":76686,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":684},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id